After some rather painful debug sessions, I discovered what the offending 
program was doing to cause Eclipse so much grief(see braindead code below). 

IMHO, the Eclipse debugger should not be knocked off its feet in this case. 
Debuggers are supposed to be used with screwed up programs(and operating 
systems, perhaps this works fine under Linux?).





public class Foo extends Thread {
    int dTime;                  // milliseconds

    public Foo(int dTime) {
        this.dTime = dTime;
    }

    public void run() {
        try {
            sleep(dTime);
        } catch(InterruptedException ie) {}
    }


	static public void main(String[] args)
	{
	  while(true)
	  {
		  Foo timer = new Foo(1000);
		  timer.start();
	  }
	}
}

Any reason we did not use synchronization instead of cloning?
I am not sure which is better in terms of performance and garbage generated.
List list = getThreadList();
synchronized(list) {
   Iterator i = list.iterator();
   while (i.hasNext()) {
        foo(i.next());
   }
}
